column31: It's #MentalHealthAwarenessWeek2023 which usually means a scattering of corporate messages telling you 'itz kk 2 not b ok.' I (Larnia, founder of Ryde hi) thought I'd expose myself on the internet in the vain hope somebody might relate and feel a bit better. Here's a timeline of my own journey with mental health and why the outdoors and wild swimming saved my life in more ways than oneüëá üì∏ 1) Depths of depression. Lost. Lonely. Breakup. Homeless. I recorded a video to myself sobbing promising myself that if I come out the other side, that we made it once and that we will again. üì∏ 2) A big sarcastic üëç up to the mental health advisor who told me to take a bath and cheer myself up. üì∏ 3) Couldn't face the outside world. Found an old notepad and tried to remember what I used to enjoy. Wrote down 'being outdoors' and 'swimming.' üì∏ 4) After months of friends, family and self care - I borrowed my parents dog and had a go at this wild swimming thing I'd read an article on. üì∏ 5) It was quite fun actually so I joined @uswimopenwater and channeled my best Ali G with a new swim cap and pair of goggs. üì∏ 6) Still a bit flat behind the old eyes but I took baby steps towards camping and getting back out in nature. üì∏ 7) Took another plunge and launched Ryde and put everything into forming a community that cared not just about product but the people wearing them. Not every day is sunshine but you have a better shot at happiness if you make time for the things you enjoy and make you feel alive. This is obviously a whirlwind overview but i'm always open to talk because there is nobody that ùò•ùò∞ùò¶ùò¥ùòØ'ùòµ struggle with mental health at some point. You are not alone. Be kind to one another, be kind to yourself and don‚Äôt be afraid to ask for help. Building a community that care about one another and self care is so important to myself and Ryde.
